  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling a tenanted investment property in Queensland involves more moving parts than a vacant sale, and the rental bond is one of the details that landlords sometimes overlook until settlement day. Unlike some aspects of the tenancy that transfer automatically, the bond requires an explicit change-of-landlord notification to the Residential Tenancies Authority. Getting this right matters for both seller and buyer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Where the bond is held</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, the rental bond is not held by the landlord or the property manager. It is lodged with the Residential Tenancies Authority (RTA), which holds it in trust for the duration of the tenancy. The landlord never has direct access to those funds during the tenancy. At the end of the tenancy, the bond is either refunded to the tenant, claimed by the landlord for rent arrears or damage, or split between the two parties if there is a partial dispute.</p>

      <p>This arrangement means the bond does not transfer as part of the property settlement the way the physical keys and title do. It remains sitting with the RTA in the tenant's name and the landlord's name as recorded on the original bond lodgement. When the landlord changes, that record needs to be updated.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens at settlement</h2>
      <p>At settlement, the outgoing landlord (the seller) and the incoming landlord (the buyer) must notify the RTA of the change of landlord. This is done via the RTA's online portal using a Change of Bond Contributor form. The purpose of the form is to update the RTA's records so that the new owner is recognised as the landlord for the purposes of any future bond claim.</p>

      <p>The RTA does not automatically update landlord details when a property changes hands. If the change-of-landlord notification is not lodged, the bond record will still show the previous owner as the contributor. This creates a practical problem at the end of the tenancy: the new owner may not be recognised as having authority to claim against the bond without additional steps to establish their landlord status.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is responsible for lodging the notification</h2>
      <p>In practice, the property manager handles the change-of-landlord notification as part of the settlement handover process. The seller's property manager will typically coordinate this with the buyer's property manager (who may be the same agency if the buyer is retaining them). Sellers should confirm with their property manager before settlement that this step is being handled and follow up promptly after settlement to make sure it has been completed.</p>

      <p>If the seller is self-managing the property, they are responsible for lodging the form themselves. The RTA's online portal is straightforward for this purpose. The notification should be lodged within a reasonable period after settlement, not left as a task to complete later.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The bond amount in Queensland</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, the maximum bond for a residential tenancy is four weeks rent for tenancies where the weekly rent is $700 or less. For tenancies above that threshold, a higher bond may be charged. The bond amount is set at the start of the tenancy and does not increase if the rent is subsequently reviewed upward during the tenancy, unless a new bond top-up is agreed and lodged.</p>

      <p>For buyers of tenanted properties, verifying that the bond has actually been lodged with the RTA is a reasonable due diligence step. A bond that was never lodged, or that was lodged incorrectly, is a risk that falls on the incoming landlord at the end of the tenancy. Your solicitor can request confirmation of bond lodgement from the seller as part of the contract process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">If there is a bond dispute at the time of sale</h2>
      <p>If the tenant has rent arrears or outstanding damage claims at the time the property is being sold, the seller faces a more complicated situation. An active or likely bond dispute complicates the settlement handover, because the incoming landlord is taking on a tenancy that may already have a contested bond claim attached to it. Sellers in this situation should discuss the position with their solicitor and property manager early, before contracts are exchanged, so that the risk can be properly allocated between the parties or resolved before settlement.</p>

      <p>A clean tenancy with a current bond lodgement, no arrears, and a cooperative tenant simplifies the process significantly. Most tenanted sales in Brisbane's inner east proceed without bond complications. But knowing the steps involved means you can confirm they have been completed rather than assuming the process takes care of itself.</p>

